{"title_page": "Wicker Park District", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:Wicker Park Historic District 2.JPG|thumb|Wicker Park Lutheran Church at Hoyne Av and LeMoyne St]]\nThe '''Wicker Park District''' is a historic district in the [[West Town, Chicago|West Town]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago, IL|Chicago]], [[Illinois]].  It is the [[Neighborhoods of Chicago|neighborhood]] bounded by Bell Avenue, Caton Street, Leavitt Street, Potomac Avenue and [[Chicago 'L']] tracks.  It was designated a [[Chicago Landmark]] on April 12, 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/W/WickerParkDistrict.html|title=Wicker Park District|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division|date=2003|accessdate=May 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe district may overlap with the [[Wicker Park Historic District]], which was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1979.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://egov.cityofchicago.org/webportal/COCWebPortal/COC_ATTACH/Community_Areas_WEST_TOWN.pdf Official City of Chicago West Town Community Map]\n*http://www.wickerpark.com\n*[http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/2159.html Chicago Encyclopedia Page]\n\n{{Chicago}}\n{{Chicago Landmark districts}}\n\n{{coords|41|54|30|N|87|40|47|W|region:US-IL_scale:10000|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Chicago Landmarks]]\n[[Category:Historic districts in Chicago]]\n\n\n{{Chicago-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:Wicker Park Historic District 2.JPG|thumb|Wicker Park Lutheran Church at Hoyne Av and LeMoyne St]]\nThe '''Wicker Park District''' is a historic district in the [[West Town, Chicago|West Town]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago, IL|Chicago]], [[Illinois]].  It is the [[Neighborhoods of Chicago|neighborhood]] bounded by Bell Avenue, Caton Street, Leavitt Street, Potomac Avenue and [[Chicago 'L']] tracks.  It was designated a [[Chicago Landmark]] on April 12, 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/W/WickerParkDistrict.html|title=Wicker Park District|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division|date=2003|accessdate=May 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe district may overlap with the [[Wicker Park Historic District]], which was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1979.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://egov.cityofchicago.org/webportal/COCWebPortal/COC_ATTACH/Community_Areas_WEST_TOWN.pdf Official City of Chicago West Town Community Map]\n*http://www.wickerpark.com\n*[http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/2159.html Chicago Encyclopedia Page]\n\n{{Chicago}}\n{{Chicago Landmark districts}}\n\n{{coords|41|54|30|N|87|40|47|W|region:US-IL_scale:10000|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Landmarks in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Historic districts in Chicago]]\n\n\n{{Chicago-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wicker_Park_District"}
{"title_page": "Omophron americanum", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of beetle}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| status = Common\n| genus = Omophron\n| species = americanum\n| authority = Dejean, 1831\n}}\n\n'''''Omophron americanum''''', the '''American round sand beetle''', is a species of [[ground beetle]] in the family [[Carabidae]]. It is found in, as well as native to, North America, ranging across most of the United States and Canada, expect British Columbia.<ref name=itis/><ref name=gbif/><ref name=buglink/><ref name=Bousquet2012/><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://entomology.museums.ualberta.ca/searching_species_details.php?fsn=Omophron+americanum&sb=1&r=1&o=1&c=2&s=1461&sn=Omophron+americanum|title=Entomology Collection > Omophron americanum|website=entomology.museums.ualberta.ca|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n''Omophron americanum'' has a broad and rather flat shape, with a length between 5.1 and 7.0 mm.<ref name=\":1\" /> A reddish-yellow with dark markings, its colour pattern is variable on its upper surface, with a darker, brown underside.<ref name=\":1\" /> It has a striated [[elytron]], a V-shaped pale area on the [[frons]], a punctuated metasternum, and two setae on the mesocoxa.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://bugguide.net/node/view/22852|title=Species Omophron americanum - American Round Sand Beetle - BugGuide.Net|website=bugguide.net|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIts habitat is the immediate vicinity of usually standing waters, on bare or sparsely vegetated sandy or clay substrates.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> It exists in altitudes between 260 and 2,200 m.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nCopulation occurs between April and May. Females are gravid (pregnant) between May and June. ''Omophron americanum'' [[Moulting|moult]] and become [[teneral]] between July and September.<ref name=\":0\" /> It overwinters in the adult stage.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n''Omophron americanum'' are gregarious.<ref name=\":0\" /> They also [[Stridulation|stridulate]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=itis>\n{{Cite web| title=''Omophron americanum'' Report\n| url=https://www.itis.gov/servlet/SingleRpt/SingleRpt?search_topic=TSN&search_value=109241\n| website=Integrated Taxonomic Information System\n| accessdate=2019-09-23\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=gbif>\n{{Cite web| title=''Omophron americanum''\n| url=https://www.gbif.org/species/1037686\n| website=GBIF\n| accessdate=2019-09-23\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=buglink>\n{{Cite web| title=''Omophron americanum'' species Information\n| url=https://bugguide.net/node/view/22852\n| website=BugGuide.net\n| accessdate=2019-09-23\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Bousquet2012>\n{{Cite journal\n| title = Catalogue of Geadephaga (Coleoptera, Adephaga) of America, north of Mexico\n| date = 2012\n| last1 = Bousquet | first1 = Yves\n| journal = ZooKeys\n| issue = 245| pages = 1\u20131722\n| url = https://zookeys.pensoft.net/articles.php?id=4003\n| doi = 10.3897/zookeys.245.3416\n| pmc=3577090\n| pmid=23431087\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| title = A revision of the genus Omophron (Coleoptera: Carabidae) of North America north of Mexico\n| date = 1956\n| last1 = Benschoter | first1 = C. A.\n| last2 = Cook | first2 = E. F.\n| journal = Annals of the Entomological Society of America\n| volume = 49| issue = 5| pages = 411\u2013429\n| url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/233680953\n| doi = 10.1093/aesa/49.5.411\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n| title = Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera, Volume 1: Archostemata - Myxophaga - Adephaga\n| date = 2017\n| editor-last1 = Lobl | editor-first1 = I.\n| editor-last2 = Smetana | editor-first2 = A.\n| publisher = Apollo Books\n| isbn = 978-90-04-33029-0\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q13919128}}\n\n[[Category:Carabidae]]\n[[Category:Articles created by Qbugbot]]\n[[Category:Beetles described in 1831]]\n\n\n{{carabidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of beetle}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| status = Common\n| genus = Omophron\n| species = americanum\n| authority = Dejean, 1831\n}}\n\n'''''Omophron americanum''''', the '''American round sand beetle''', is a species of [[ground beetle]] in the family [[Carabidae]]. It is found in as well as native to North America, ranging across most of the United States and Canada, expect British Columbia.<ref name=itis/><ref name=gbif/><ref name=buglink/><ref name=Bousquet2012/><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://entomology.museums.ualberta.ca/searching_species_details.php?fsn=Omophron+americanum&sb=1&r=1&o=1&c=2&s=1461&sn=Omophron+americanum|title=Entomology Collection > Omophron americanum|website=entomology.museums.ualberta.ca|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n''Omophron americanum'' has a broad and rather flat shape, with a length between 5.1 and 7.0 mm.<ref name=\":1\" /> A reddish-yellow with dark markings, its colour pattern is variable on its upper surface, with a darker, brown underside.<ref name=\":1\" /> It has a striated [[elytron]], a V-shaped pale area on the [[frons]], a punctuated metasternum, and two setae on the mesocoxa.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://bugguide.net/node/view/22852|title=Species Omophron americanum - American Round Sand Beetle - BugGuide.Net|website=bugguide.net|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIts habitat is the immediate vicinity of usually standing waters, on bare or sparsely vegetated sandy or clay substrates.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> It exists in altitudes between 260 and 2,200 m.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nCopulation occurs between April and May. Females are gravid (pregnant) between May and June. ''Omophron americanum'' [[Moulting|moult]] and become [[teneral]] between July and September.<ref name=\":0\" /> It overwinters in the adult stage.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n''Omophron americanum'' are gregarious.<ref name=\":0\" /> They also [[Stridulation|stridulate]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=itis>\n{{Cite web| title=''Omophron americanum'' Report\n| url=https://www.itis.gov/servlet/SingleRpt/SingleRpt?search_topic=TSN&search_value=109241\n| website=Integrated Taxonomic Information System\n| accessdate=2019-09-23\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=gbif>\n{{Cite web| title=''Omophron americanum''\n| url=https://www.gbif.org/species/1037686\n| website=GBIF\n| accessdate=2019-09-23\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=buglink>\n{{Cite web| title=''Omophron americanum'' species Information\n| url=https://bugguide.net/node/view/22852\n| website=BugGuide.net\n| accessdate=2019-09-23\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Bousquet2012>\n{{Cite journal\n| title = Catalogue of Geadephaga (Coleoptera, Adephaga) of America, north of Mexico\n| date = 2012\n| last1 = Bousquet | first1 = Yves\n| journal = ZooKeys\n| issue = 245| pages = 1\u20131722\n| url = https://zookeys.pensoft.net/articles.php?id=4003\n| doi = 10.3897/zookeys.245.3416\n| pmc=3577090\n| pmid=23431087\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| title = A revision of the genus Omophron (Coleoptera: Carabidae) of North America north of Mexico\n| date = 1956\n| last1 = Benschoter | first1 = C. A.\n| last2 = Cook | first2 = E. F.\n| journal = Annals of the Entomological Society of America\n| volume = 49| issue = 5| pages = 411\u2013429\n| url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/233680953\n| doi = 10.1093/aesa/49.5.411\n}}\n* {{Cite book\n| title = Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera, Volume 1: Archostemata - Myxophaga - Adephaga\n| date = 2017\n| editor-last1 = Lobl | editor-first1 = I.\n| editor-last2 = Smetana | editor-first2 = A.\n| publisher = Apollo Books\n| isbn = 978-90-04-33029-0\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q13919128}}\n\n[[Category:Carabidae]]\n[[Category:Articles created by Qbugbot]]\n[[Category:Beetles described in 1831]]\n\n\n{{carabidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Harrumphings", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omophron_americanum"}
{"title_page": "West Argyle Street Historic District", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = West Argyle Street Historic District\n| added = June 3, 2010\n| locmapin = Chicago#Illinois#USA\n| image = Argyle CTA 20100729.jpg\n| caption =West Argyle Street, at the [[Argyle (CTA)|Argyle 'L' station]]\n| location= [[Chicago]], Illinois\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|58|24|N|87|39|25|W|display=inline,title}}\n| area =\n| built =\n| architect= Multiple\n| refnum= 10000311\n}}\nThe '''West Argyle Street Historic District''' (also known as \"Little Saigon\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2007-11-29-0711270340-story.html |title=THE ESSENTIALS: Argyle Street |last=Eng |first=Monica |publisher=Chicago Tribune |date=November 29, 2017 |website=Chicago Tribune |access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> \"New Chinatown\", \"Argyle Square\",  \"Asia on Argyle\",  or \"Argyle Park\") is a [[Historic district (United States)|historic district]] in the northern [[Uptown, Chicago|Uptown]], a commercial district of [[Chicago]], Illinois. It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on June 3, 2010. The community covers an area of about {{convert|41|acre|km2}}; its rough boundaries are N. Glenwood Ave to the west, Winona Street to the north, [[Sheridan Road]] to the east, and Ainslie Street to the south. It was home to the Essenay Studios in the 1920s founded by Charlie Chaplain, a producer of silent movies before relocating to Southern California in Hollywood. Essenay Studios now is home to St. Augustine College.\n\n==History==\nThe area covered by the historic district originally developed in the 1880s as a suburb called ''Argyle Park''. The suburb had been named by Chicago Alderman and developer James A. Campbell for his ancestors the [[Duke of Argyll|Dukes of Argyll]] in Scotland.<ref>{{cite book|last=Callary|first=Edward|title=Place names of Illinois|year=2009|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=0-252-03356-6|page=13}}</ref> Development was centered on a station on the new Chicago & Evanston line of the [[Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway]] that opened in May 1885.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Chicago & Evanston|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=May 22, 1885}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Suburban|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=November 8, 1885}}</ref> The village, along with the rest of the [[Lake View, Chicago#Lake View Township|Lake View Township]], was annexed into Chicago in 1889.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ten New Sister Wards|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=July 20, 1889}}</ref> In 1908 the [[Northwestern Elevated Railroad]] was extended north from Wilson Avenue, using the tracks of the Chicago, Milwaukee & St. Paul Railroad,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Electrification of the Evanston Suburban Line of the Chicago Milwaukee & St. Paul|journal=The Railway Age|date=October 4, 1907|volume=44|issue=14|page=467|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D5RMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA467|accessdate=July 29, 2010}}</ref> This linked the suburb into Chicago's [[Chicago 'L'|'L' network]], and the area became popular with people of limited means who wanted to live on the [[Lake Michigan]] shore.<ref name=\"CBS2\">{{cite web|title=Uptown's Argyle Street Named To Historic Register |url=http://cbs2chicago.com/local/argyle.street.historic.2.1750415.html |work=CBS2 Chicago: Chicago Area Local News |publisher=CBS Broadcasting Inc |accessdate=July 29, 2010 |date=June 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621030820/http://cbs2chicago.com/local/argyle.street.historic.2.1750415.html |archive-date=June 21, 2010 }}</ref> The railroad tracks were elevated onto an embankment between 1914 and 1922.\n[[File:Argyle restaurants 20100729.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Restaurants in a single story building on a street corner|Vietnamese and Thai restaurants at the corner of Argyle Street and Broadway]]\nChicago restaurateur Jimmy Wong bought property in the area in the 1960s and planned its rebirth as ''New Chinatown''. He envisioned a mall with pagodas, trees and reflecting ponds to replace the empty storefronts.<ref name=\"Tribune20010706\">{{cite news|last=Madhani|first=Aamer|title=Jimmy Wong 1914-2001 - Restaurateur helped start `new Chinatown'|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=July 6, 2001}}</ref> The [[Hip Sing Association]], a Chinese cultural group, moved its Chicago offices to Argyle Street in 1971,<ref name=\"Tribune 19860331\">{{cite news|last=Congbalay|first=Dean|title=Argyle Street shopping strip weaves pattern of prosperity|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=March 31, 1986}}</ref> and by 1974 Wong and the Hip Sing Association owned 80% of the three-block stretch on Argyle. Wong had an accident and broke both hips, leaving him unable to follow through on his plans. In 1979 Charlie Soo, founder of the Asian American Small Business Association, took up the cause, and the area developed not solely as a Chinese enclave but also including Vietnamese, Laotian, Cambodian, and Japanese businesses.<ref>{{cite news|last=Heise|first=Kenan|title=N. Side's Argyle Street takes on Far East flavor|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=November 20, 1981}}</ref> Soo campaigned to get the [[Chicago Transit Authority]] to give the [[Argyle (CTA)|Argyle 'L' station]] a $250,000 face-lift, then in 1981 he started the \"Taste of Argyle,\" an annual food festival. He also secured funds from Chicago Mayor [[Jane Byrne]] to fix the sidewalks, and later from Mayor [[Harold Washington]] to repair building facades. Because of his tireless work in promoting the neighborhood, Soo would later be known as the unofficial \"Mayor of Argyle Street.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Charlie Soo 1945-2001: Argyle Street 'Mayor,' bold promoter of Asian shops|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=April 4, 2001|author=Lynch, Kevin|author2=Janega, James}}</ref> By 1986 it was estimated that Uptown had about 8000 Chinese and Vietnamese residents.<ref name=\"Tribune 19860331\" />\n\nThe concentration of Vietnamese restaurants, bakeries and shops; as well as Chinese, Cambodian, Laotian and Thai businesses along Argyle Street, centered on the Argyle 'L' station has led to the neighborhood being nicknamed ''New Chinatown'', ''Little Saigon'', or ''Little Vietnam''.<ref name=\"CBS2\" /> On June 3, 2010 the area roughly bounded by [[Broadway Street (Chicago)|Broadway]] to the west, Winona Street to the north, [[Sheridan Road]] to the east, and Ainslie Street to the south was entered into the National Register of Historic Places.<ref name=\"CBS2\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Weekly list of actions taken on properties:   6/01/10  through  6/04/10|url=http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/listings/20100611.htm|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=July 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Chicago]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|position=left}}\n\n{{Neighborhoods in Chicago}}\n{{Chicago}}\n{{Ethnic enclaves}}\n{{US Chinatowns}}\n{{Registered Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Historic districts in Chicago]]\n[[Category:North Side, Chicago]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Asian-American culture in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Ethnic enclaves in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Cambodian-American culture]]\n[[Category:Chinatowns in the United States]]\n[[Category:Little Saigons]]\n[[Category:Laotian-American culture]]\n[[Category:Thai-American culture]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese-American history]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 1880s]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = West Argyle Street Historic District\n| added = June 3, 2010\n| locmapin = Chicago#Illinois#USA\n| image = Argyle CTA 20100729.jpg\n| caption =West Argyle Street, at the [[Argyle (CTA)|Argyle 'L' station]]\n| location= [[Chicago]], Illinois\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|58|24|N|87|39|25|W|display=inline,title}}\n| area =\n| built =\n| architect= Multiple\n| refnum= 10000311\n}}\nThe '''West Argyle Street Historic District''' (also known as \"Little Saigon\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2007-11-29-0711270340-story.html |title=THE ESSENTIALS: Argyle Street |last=Eng |first=Monica |publisher=Chicago Tribune |date=November 29, 2017 |website=Chicago Tribune |access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> \"New Chinatown\", \"Argyle Square\",  \"Asia on Argyle\",  or \"Argyle Park\") is a [[Historic district (United States)|historic district]] in the northern [[Uptown, Chicago|Uptown]], a commercial district of [[Chicago]], Illinois. It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on June 3, 2010. The community covers an area of about {{convert|41|acre|km2}}; its rough boundaries are N. Glenwood Ave to the west, Winona Street to the north, [[Sheridan Road]] to the east, and Ainslie Street to the south. It was home to the Essenay Studios in the 1920s founded by Charlie Chaplain, a producer of silent movies before relocating to Southern California in Hollywood. Essenay Studios now is home to St. Augustine College.\n\n==History==\nThe area covered by the historic district originally developed in the 1880s as a suburb called ''Argyle Park''. The suburb had been named by Chicago Alderman and developer James A. Campbell for his ancestors the [[Duke of Argyll|Dukes of Argyll]] in Scotland.<ref>{{cite book|last=Callary|first=Edward|title=Place names of Illinois|year=2009|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=0-252-03356-6|page=13}}</ref> Development was centered on a station on the new Chicago & Evanston line of the [[Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway]] that opened in May 1885.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Chicago & Evanston|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=May 22, 1885}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Suburban|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=November 8, 1885}}</ref> The village, along with the rest of the [[Lake View, Chicago#Lake View Township|Lake View Township]], was annexed into Chicago in 1889.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ten New Sister Wards|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=July 20, 1889}}</ref> In 1908 the [[Northwestern Elevated Railroad]] was extended north from Wilson Avenue, using the tracks of the Chicago, Milwaukee & St. Paul Railroad,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Electrification of the Evanston Suburban Line of the Chicago Milwaukee & St. Paul|journal=The Railway Age|date=October 4, 1907|volume=44|issue=14|page=467|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D5RMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA467|accessdate=July 29, 2010}}</ref> This linked the suburb into Chicago's [[Chicago 'L'|'L' network]], and the area became popular with people of limited means who wanted to live on the [[Lake Michigan]] shore.<ref name=\"CBS2\">{{cite web|title=Uptown's Argyle Street Named To Historic Register |url=http://cbs2chicago.com/local/argyle.street.historic.2.1750415.html |work=CBS2 Chicago: Chicago Area Local News |publisher=CBS Broadcasting Inc |accessdate=July 29, 2010 |date=June 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621030820/http://cbs2chicago.com/local/argyle.street.historic.2.1750415.html |archive-date=June 21, 2010 }}</ref> The railroad tracks were elevated onto an embankment between 1914 and 1922.\n[[File:Argyle restaurants 20100729.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Restaurants in a single story building on a street corner|Vietnamese and Thai restaurants at the corner of Argyle Street and Broadway]]\nChicago restaurateur Jimmy Wong bought property in the area in the 1960s and planned its rebirth as ''New Chinatown''. He envisioned a mall with pagodas, trees and reflecting ponds to replace the empty storefronts.<ref name=\"Tribune20010706\">{{cite news|last=Madhani|first=Aamer|title=Jimmy Wong 1914-2001 - Restaurateur helped start `new Chinatown'|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=July 6, 2001}}</ref> The [[Hip Sing Association]], a Chinese cultural group, moved its Chicago offices to Argyle Street in 1971,<ref name=\"Tribune 19860331\">{{cite news|last=Congbalay|first=Dean|title=Argyle Street shopping strip weaves pattern of prosperity|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=March 31, 1986}}</ref> and by 1974 Wong and the Hip Sing Association owned 80% of the three-block stretch on Argyle. Wong had an accident and broke both hips, leaving him unable to follow through on his plans. In 1979 Charlie Soo, founder of the Asian American Small Business Association, took up the cause, and the area developed not solely as a Chinese enclave but also including Vietnamese, Laotian, Cambodian, and Japanese businesses.<ref>{{cite news|last=Heise|first=Kenan|title=N. Side's Argyle Street takes on Far East flavor|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=November 20, 1981}}</ref> Soo campaigned to get the [[Chicago Transit Authority]] to give the [[Argyle (CTA)|Argyle 'L' station]] a $250,000 face-lift, then in 1981 he started the \"Taste of Argyle,\" an annual food festival. He also secured funds from Chicago Mayor [[Jane Byrne]] to fix the sidewalks, and later from Mayor [[Harold Washington]] to repair building facades. Because of his tireless work in promoting the neighborhood, Soo would later be known as the unofficial \"Mayor of Argyle Street.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Charlie Soo 1945-2001: Argyle Street 'Mayor,' bold promoter of Asian shops|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=April 4, 2001|author=Lynch, Kevin|author2=Janega, James}}</ref> By 1986 it was estimated that Uptown had about 8000 Chinese and Vietnamese residents.<ref name=\"Tribune 19860331\" />\n\nThe concentration of Vietnamese restaurants, bakeries and shops; as well as Chinese, Cambodian, Laotian and Thai businesses along Argyle Street, centered on the Argyle 'L' station has led to the neighborhood being nicknamed ''New Chinatown'', ''Little Saigon'', or ''Little Vietnam''.<ref name=\"CBS2\" /> On June 3, 2010 the area roughly bounded by [[Broadway Street (Chicago)|Broadway]] to the west, Winona Street to the north, [[Sheridan Road]] to the east, and Ainslie Street to the south was entered into the National Register of Historic Places.<ref name=\"CBS2\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Weekly list of actions taken on properties:   6/01/10  through  6/04/10|url=http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/listings/20100611.htm|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=July 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Chicago]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|position=left}}\n\n{{Chicago Landmark districts}}\n{{Neighborhoods in Chicago}}\n{{Chicago}}\n{{Ethnic enclaves}}\n{{US Chinatowns}}\n{{Registered Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Historic districts in Chicago]]\n[[Category:North Side, Chicago]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Asian-American culture in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Ethnic enclaves in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Cambodian-American culture]]\n[[Category:Chinatowns in the United States]]\n[[Category:Little Saigons]]\n[[Category:Laotian-American culture]]\n[[Category:Thai-American culture]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese-American history]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 1880s]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Argyle_Street_Historic_District"}
