er from ''[[Grand Blue]]''\n*{{Nihongo|Azusa Sawa|\u6fa4 \u6893|}}, one of the supporting protagonists from ''[[Girls und Panzer]]''\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese feminine given names]]\n", "text_old": "'''Azusa''' (\u6893, \u3042\u305a\u3055) is a Japanese feminine given name, literally meaning \"[[catalpa]]\" among other senses (other trees, and objects made from this wood). Notable people with the name include:\n\n*[[Azusa Iwashimizu]], Japanese association footballer\n*[[Azusa Nakao]], Japanese voice actress\n*[[Azusa Nojiri]] (born 1982), Japanese marathon runner\n*[[Azusa Tadokoro]], Japanese voice actress\n*[[Azusa Togashi]], Japanese gravure idol\n*{{Nihongo|[[Azusa Watanabe]]|\u6e21\u8fba \u6893||born 1969}}, Japanese actress\n*{{Nihongo|[[Azusa Yamamoto]]|\u5c71\u672c \u6893||born 1981}}, Japanese gravure idol, actress and television personality\n\n== Fictional characters==\n*Azusa Miura, a character from ''[[The Idolmaster]]''\n*Azusa \"Azu-nyan\" Nakano, a main character from ''[[K-On!]]''\n*Azusa Enomoto, a character from ''[[Case Closed]]''\n*Azusa Hanai, a character from ''[[Big Windup!]]''\n*Azusa Azuki, the main character from ''[[The \"Hentai\" Prince and the Stony Cat.]]''\n*Azusa Kinose, a character from ''[[Starry Sky]]''\n*Azusa Mukami,  a character from [[Diabolik Lovers]]\n*Azusa Nakajo, a character from ''[[The Irregular at Magic High School]]''\n*Azusa Asahina, a character from ''[[Brothers Conflict]]''\n*Azusa Hamaoka, a character from ''[[Grand Blue]]''\n*Azusa Sawa, one of the supporting protagonists from ''[[Girls und Panzer]]''\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese feminine given names]]\n", "name_user": "CodyBeaulieu", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Azusa_(given_name)"}
{"title_page": "Marlene Sai", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Marlene Sai\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1941|12|14}}\n| birth_place  = [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]]\n| years_active = 1959\u2013present\n| spouse       = Herb Cockett <small>(divorced)</small>\n| children     = Cassie Cockett, Mahela Cockett\n| occupation   = Singer, actress\n| website      = [http://www.marlenesai.com marlenesai.com]\n}}\n\n'''Marlene Sai''' is a Hawaiian classic-style female solo singer,<ref name=\"hawaiianmusichistory\">{{cite web |title=Marlene Sai Bio and Photos |publisher=Hawaiian Music History |url=http://www.hawaiianmusichistory.com/artists/marlene-sai.htm |accessdate=August 28, 2016}}</ref> born in Honolulu of Hawaiian\u2013Chinese heritage. The ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' refers to Marlene Sai as one of the true icons of the islands.<ref name=\"sfgate\">{{cite news |title=Islands icon Marlene Sai on rare California concert tour |author=Jeanne Cooper |date=March 31, 2011 |publisher=SFGate |url=http://blog.sfgate.com/hawaii/2011/03/31/islands-icon-marlene-sai-on-rare-california-concert-tour/}}</ref> The ''[[Santa Cruz Sentinel]]'' refers to Sai as a [[living legend (person)|living legend]] of Hawaiian music.<ref name=\"santacruzsentinel\">{{cite news |author=Norman Markowitz |date=March 31, 2011 |title=Hawaiian legend Marlene Sai headlines Don Quixote's |newspaper=[[Santa Cruz Sentinel]] |url=http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/general-news/20110331/hawaiian-legend-marlene-sai-headlines-don-quixotes}}</ref> [[PBS Hawaii]]'s Leslie Wilcox says of Sai \"There are only a handful of true divas in Hawaiian music, women who wrap their powerful voices with grace, elegance and beauty. You can add to the list Marlene Sai.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Guest: Marlene Sai |work=Long Story Short with Leslie Wilcox |date=August 18, 2009 |publisher=PBS Hawaii |url=http://www.pbshawaii.org/ourproductions/longstory_transcripts/LSS%20304-305%20Transcript%20%20-%20Marlene%20Sai.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nSai is from [[Kaimuki, Hawaii]], and a product of the [[Kamehameha Schools|Kamehameha school]] system.<ref>{{cite web |title=Marlene Sai: Hawaiian Music \"Diva\" |work=Long Story Short with Leslie Wilcox |date=August 18, 2009 |publisher=PBS Hawaii |url=http://www.pbshawaii.org/ourproductions/longstory_guests/sai.htm}}</ref> She released her first record in 1959. Sai was taught the basics of singing and mentored by her uncle Andy Cummings, considered another legend of Hawaiian singing and songwriting.<ref name=\"santacruzsentinel\" /> Cummings taught his niece the love song \"Kainoa\" written by his friend Jimmy Taka when he found out he was dying of cancer. The song was for his wife. Cummings put the song down on paper and later taught it to his then-teenage niece, Marlene Sai. \"Kainoa\" went on to become Sai's first hit and title for her debut album.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hawai\u02bbi Music Pupu Platter\t|author=Ronna Bolante |author2=Michael Keany |date=June 1, 2004 |work=[[Honolulu (magazine)|Honolulu]] |url=http://www.honolulumagazine.com/Honolulu-Magazine/June-2004/Hawaiai-Music-Pupu-Platter/}}</ref> Sai was discovered by Hawaiian entertainer [[Don Ho]] before he was famous while managing his mother's restaurant lounge Honey's in [[Kaneohe]] on the island of [[Oahu]].<ref name=\"hawaiianmusichistory\" />\n\n==Singing==\nMarlene Sai, just out of high school, became a teenage recording star. Sai toured [[Japan]] in 1962 and has an extensive following there.<ref name=\"sfgate\" /> In 2007 Sai hosted the 23rd annual Ka Himeni Ana singing contest at the [[Hawaii Theatre]]. In 2008, Sai performed in concert in New York City at [[Carnegie Hall]].<ref name=\"santacruzsentinel\" /> Sai's album Kainoa was considered 21st out of 50 of the all-time great albums of Hawaii by ''Honolulu'' magazine in 2004. In the article it states that it wasn't recorded under the most ideal circumstances. When she signed with Sounds of Hawaii, the new label hadn't even finished building its studio. Kainoa was recorded inside the bus depot once located on King Street. \"We recorded late at night, when it was quiet, buses weren't moving and you hoped an airplane didn't fly overhead,\" Sai says. \"But I had Sonny Chillingworth on slack key and Don Ho on the organ behind me, so we still had a ball.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=The 50 Greatest Hawai'i Albums of All Time |author=Ronna Bolante |author2=Michael Keany |date=June 1, 2004 |work=[[Honolulu (magazine)|Honolulu]] |url=http://www.honolulumagazine.com/Honolulu-Magazine/June-2004/The-50-Greatest-Hawaii-Albums-of-All-Time/}}</ref>\n\n===Records and CDs===\n*''Kainoa'' 1959\n*''Sweet Someone''\n*''Best Of Marlene Sai'' 1967\n*''Hana Hou''\n*''Not Pau''\n*''Marlene Sai'' 1985\n*''I Love You'' 1994\n*''Mele No Ka {{okina}}Oe'' 1996\n*''Marlene & Mahela'' 1999\n*''Legacy'' 2010\n\n==Acting==\nIn 1986, Sai played Makua Wahine Luka in the TV series ''Magnum PI''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Marlene Sai |publisher=IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2619045/}}</ref>\nIn 1987, Sai starred in a one-actress play called ''Hear Me, O My People''. In it she portrayed Queen [[Liliuokalani|Lili{{okina}}uokalani]]. She was also invited to perform the play for members of the United States Congress at the [[Folger Library|Folger Shakespeare Theatre]] in Washington, D.C. Sai also portrayed Queen Lili{{okina}}uokalani, Hawaii's last monarch, in the PBS documentary ''Betrayal''. The made-for-TV film premiered in Hawaii on January 17, 1993, on the 100th anniversary of the overthrow it depicted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaiifilmoffice.com/hawaii-a-filmography/television-productions |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928142426/http://www.hawaiifilmoffice.com/hawaii-a-filmography/television-productions |archivedate=2011-09-28 }}</ref> Sai portrayed Bloody Mary in the 2007\u20132008 Hawaii Opera Theatre's production of ''South Pacific'' in Blaisdell Concert Hall in Honolulu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.midweek.com/content/columns/oldfriends_article/marlene_sai |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024175945/http://www.midweek.com/content/columns/oldfriends_article/marlene_sai/ |archivedate=2008-10-24 }}</ref> In 2008 Sai starred in the dinner show ''This Is Hawai'i'' at the Hale Koa Hotel.\n\n==Recognition and awards==\nIn 1986, Sai received the [[Hawai'i Academy of Recording Arts]] (HARA) [[Na Hoku Hanohano Award]] for 'Best Female Vocalist'<ref name=\"hawaiianmusichistory\" /> In 1987, Sai was given the \"Po'okela Award\" from the Hawaii State Theatre Council for her portrayal of Queen Lili{{okina}}uokalani in a one-actress play called ''Hear Me, O My People''.<ref name=\"santacruzsentinel\" /> In 2004, HARA honored her with Na Hoku Hanohano Lifetime Achievement Award for her accomplishments in music and recording.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tgif.staradvertiser.com/archives/tag/hara |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110418092608/http://tgif.staradvertiser.com/archives/tag/hara |archivedate=2011-04-18 }}</ref> In September 2007, she was inducted into the [[Hawaiian Music Hall of Fame]] by the Hawaiian Music Foundation. Her first LP release, ''Kainoa'', was included in the book \"The 50 Greatest Hawaii Albums\".\n\n==Other interest==\nSai is currently president of the Hawaii Academy of Recording Arts and on the board of the Honolulu Boys Choir and the Mayor's Office of Culture and the Arts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.midweek.com/content/columns/oldfriends_article/marlene_sai/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024175945/http://www.midweek.com/content/columns/oldfriends_article/marlene_sai/ |archivedate=2008-10-24 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Hawaiian Music Hall of Fame}}\n\n