as an extensive following there.<ref name=\"sfgate\" /> In 2007 Sai hosted the 23rd annual Ka Himeni Ana singing contest at the [[Hawaii Theatre]]. In 2008, Sai performed in concert in New York City at [[Carnegie Hall]].<ref name=\"santacruzsentinel\" /> Sai's album Kainoa was considered 21st out of 50 of the all-time great albums of Hawaii by ''Honolulu'' magazine in 2004. In the article it states that it wasn't recorded under the most ideal circumstances. When she signed with Sounds of Hawaii, the new label hadn't even finished building its studio. Kainoa was recorded inside the bus depot once located on King Street. \"We recorded late at night, when it was quiet, buses weren't moving and you hoped an airplane didn't fly overhead,\" Sai says. \"But I had Sonny Chillingworth on slack key and Don Ho on the organ behind me, so we still had a ball.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=The 50 Greatest Hawai'i Albums of All Time |author=Ronna Bolante |author2=Michael Keany |date=June 1, 2004 |work=[[Honolulu (magazine)|Honolulu]] |url=http://www.honolulumagazine.com/Honolulu-Magazine/June-2004/The-50-Greatest-Hawaii-Albums-of-All-Time/}}</ref>\n\n===Records and CDs===\n*''Kainoa 1959\n*''Sweet Someone\n*''Best Of Marlene Sai 1967\n*''Hana Hou\n*''Not Pau\n*''Marlene Sai 1985\n*''I Love You 1994\n*''Mele No Ka {{okina}}Oe 1996\n*''Marlene & Mahela 1999\n*''Legacy 2010\n\n==Acting==\nIn 1986, Sai played Makua Wahine Luka in the TV series ''Magnum PI''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Marlene Sai |publisher=IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2619045/}}</ref>\nIn 1987, Sai starred in a one-actress play called ''Hear Me, O My People''. In it she portrayed Queen [[Liliuokalani|Lili{{okina}}uokalani]]. She was also invited to perform the play for members of the United States Congress at the [[Folger Library|Folger Shakespeare Theatre]] in Washington, D.C. Sai also portrayed Queen Lili{{okina}}uokalani, Hawaii's last monarch, in the PBS documentary ''Betrayal''. The made-for-TV film premiered in Hawaii on January 17, 1993, on the 100th anniversary of the overthrow it depicted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaiifilmoffice.com/hawaii-a-filmography/television-productions |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928142426/http://www.hawaiifilmoffice.com/hawaii-a-filmography/television-productions |archivedate=2011-09-28 }}</ref> Sai portrayed Bloody Mary in the 2007\u20132008 Hawaii Opera Theatre's production of ''South Pacific'' in Blaisdell Concert Hall in Honolulu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.midweek.com/content/columns/oldfriends_article/marlene_sai |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024175945/http://www.midweek.com/content/columns/oldfriends_article/marlene_sai/ |archivedate=2008-10-24 }}</ref> In 2008 Sai starred in the dinner show ''This Is Hawai'i'' at the Hale Koa Hotel.\n\n==Recognition and awards==\nIn 1986, Sai received the [[Hawai'i Academy of Recording Arts]] (HARA) [[Na Hoku Hanohano Award]] for 'Best Female Vocalist'<ref name=\"hawaiianmusichistory\" /> In 1987, Sai was given the \"Po'okela Award\" from the Hawaii State Theatre Council for her portrayal of Queen Lili{{okina}}uokalani in a one-actress play called ''Hear Me, O My People''.<ref name=\"santacruzsentinel\" /> In 2004, HARA honored her with Na Hoku Hanohano Lifetime Achievement Award for her accomplishments in music and recording.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tgif.staradvertiser.com/archives/tag/hara |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110418092608/http://tgif.staradvertiser.com/archives/tag/hara |archivedate=2011-04-18 }}</ref> In September 2007, she was inducted into the [[Hawaiian Music Hall of Fame]] by the Hawaiian Music Foundation. Her first LP release, ''Kainoa'', was included in the book \"The 50 Greatest Hawaii Albums\".\n\n==Other interest==\nSai is currently president of the Hawaii Academy of Recording Arts and on the board of the Honolulu Boys Choir and the Mayor's Office of Culture and the Arts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.midweek.com/content/columns/oldfriends_article/marlene_sai/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024175945/http://www.midweek.com/content/columns/oldfriends_article/marlene_sai/ |archivedate=2008-10-24 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Hawaiian Music Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sai, Marlene}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Honolulu]]\n[[Category:Kamehameha Schools alumni]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Honolulu]]\n[[Category:Traditional pop music singers]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American female singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Native Hawaiian actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Jonesey95", "label": "safe", "comment": "FixLintererrors usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marlene_Sai"}
{"title_page": "Alfredo De Quesada", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=June 2019}}\n'''Alfredo De Quesada del Toro''' is a Puerto Rican film, television and theatre actor. He\u2019s the cousin of actor Benicio del Toro.\n\nBorn in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Puerto Rico]] to Cuban immigrants who resettled in Puerto Rico, De Quesada was raised in San Juan where he attended [[Colegio San Ignacio de Loyola]] and went on to graduate with double major in General Management and Theatre Arts from the [[Carroll School of Management]] of [[Boston College]] (Chestnut Hill, MA).  During college he was part of the oldest college improv comedy troupe My Mother's Fleabag, and, upon graduation, moved to [[New York City]].  There he worked regularly with the premiere Hispanic theater company [http://www.repertorio.org/ Repertorio Espa\u00f1ol], and was cast in the internationally acclaimed Argentinean aerial experimental theatre troupe [https://web.archive.org/web/20060824201857/http://www.delaguarda.com/ De La Guarda.]\n\nMost of his national recognition came when competing in the [[Telemundo]] produced reality show ''Protagonistas de Novela 2'', which showcased him as a superior actor in contrast to the rest of the contestants.\n\nHe has had guest starring roles in many TV series including ''[[Strangers with Candy]]'', ''[[Upright Citizens Brigade]]'', ''[[One Life to Live]]'', ''[[The Blacklist: Redemption]]'', ''[[Law & Order]]'', ''[[The Knick]]'', and ''[[Orange Is the New Black]]''.\n\nHe played the part of Israel Pardo in the film ''[[Che (2008 film)|Che]]'' by [[Steven Soderbergh]].\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1755961}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quesada, Alfredo De}}\n[[Category:Boston College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican male film actors]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican male television actors]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=June 2019}}\n'''Alfredo De Quesada''' is a Puerto Rican film, television and theatre actor.\n\nBorn in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Puerto Rico]] to Cuban immigrants who resettled in Puerto Rico, De Quesada was raised in San Juan where he attended [[Colegio San Ignacio de Loyola]] and went on to graduate with double major in General Management and Theatre Arts from the [[Carroll School of Management]] of [[Boston College]] (Chestnut Hill, MA).  During college he was part of the oldest college improv comedy troupe My Mother's Fleabag, and, upon graduation, moved to [[New York City]].  There he worked regularly with the premiere Hispanic theater company [http://www.repertorio.org/ Repertorio Espa\u00f1ol], and was cast in the internationally acclaimed Argentinean aerial experimental theatre troupe [https://web.archive.org/web/20060824201857/http://www.delaguarda.com/ De La Guarda.]\n\nMost of his national recognition came when competing in the [[Telemundo]] produced reality show ''Protagonistas de Novela 2'', which showcased him as a superior actor in contrast to the rest of the contestants.\n\nHe has had guest starring roles in many TV series including ''[[Strangers with Candy]]'', ''[[Upright Citizens Brigade]]'', ''[[One Life to Live]]'', ''[[The Blacklist: Redemption]]'', ''[[Law & Order]]'', ''[[The Knick]]'', and ''[[Orange Is the New Black]]''.\n\nHe played the part of Israel Pardo in the film ''[[Che (2008 film)|Che]]'' by [[Steven Soderbergh]].\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1755961}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quesada, Alfredo De}}\n[[Category:Boston College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican male film actors]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican male television actors]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "24.48.215.37", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfredo_De_Quesada"}
{"title_page": "Pedro Pierluisi", "text_new": "{{short description|Puerto Rican politician}}\n{{spanish name|Pierluisi|Urrutia}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Pedro R. Pierluisi\n| image = Pedro-Pierluisi-cropped.jpg\n<!-- While his swearing in was deemed unconstitutional and he was duly removed from office on August 7, 2019, it is undeniable that Pierluisi did indeed serve and occupy the post of Governor and it should remain in the infobox. The details of his short term should be described in the prose as supported by reliable sourcing. -->\n| office = [[Governor of Puerto Rico]]<br>''{{small|[[De facto]]}}''\n| term_start = August 2, 2019\n| term_end = August 7, 2019{{efn|Pierluisi was removed on August 7, 2019, via ''[[quo warranto]]''. Hence, his tenure is now considered only ''[[de facto]]''.}}\n| predecessor = [[Ricardo Rossell\u00f3]]\n| successor = [[Wanda V\u00e1zquez Garced]]\n<!-- While his swearing in was deemed unconstitutional and he was duly removed from office on August 7, 2019, it is undeniable that Pierluisi did indeed serve and occupy the post of Governor and it should remain in the infobox. The details of his short term should be described in the prose as supported by reliable sourcing. -->\n| office1 = Acting [[Secretary of State of Puerto Rico]]\n| governor1 = [[Ricardo Rossell\u00f3]]\n| term_start1 = July 31, 2019\n| term_end1 = August 2, 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Luis G. Rivera Mar\u00edn|Luis Rivera Mar\u00edn]]\n| successor1 = [[Elmer Rom\u00e1n]]\n| office2 = [[Resident Commissioner of Puerto Rico]]\n| term_start2 = January 3, 2009\n| term_end2 = January 3, 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]]\n| successor2 = [[Jenniffer Gonz\u00e1lez]]\n| office3 = [[Secretary of Justice of Puerto Rico]]\n| governor3 = [[Pedro Rossell\u00f3]]\n| term_start3 = January 2, 1993\n| term_end3 = January 2, 1997\n| predecessor3 = H\u00e9ctor Rivera Cruz\n| successor3 = Jos\u00e9 Fuentes Agostini\n| birth_name = Pedro Rafael Pierluisi Urrutia\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|4|26}}\n| birth_place = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Puerto Rico]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[New Progressive Party of Puerto Rico|New Progressive]]\n| otherparty = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| children = 4\n| education = [[Tulane University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])<br />[[George Washington University]] ([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]])\n| relations = [[Jos\u00e9 Jaime Pierluisi]] (brother)<br />\n}}\n'''Pedro Pierluisi Urrutia'''{{efn|Primera Hora (2009) \"El nuevo comisionado residente en Washington, Pedro Rafael Pierluisi Urrutia...\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.primerahora.com/noticias/gobierno-politica/nota/buscaauxiliofederal-261641/ |title=Busca auxilio federal |date={{date|2009-01-07|mdy}} |newspaper=[[Primera Hora (Puerto Rico)|Primera Hora]] |language=Spanish |accessdate={{date|2013-09-02|mdy}} }}</ref>}} (born April 26, 1959) is a Puerto Rican [[lawyer|attorney]], lobbyist,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.senado.pr.gov:443/Pages/Registro-de-Cabilderos.aspx|title=Senado Registro de Cabilderos|website=www.senado.pr.gov|language=es|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref> and politician who served as ''[[de facto]]'' [[governor of Puerto Rico]] from August 2 to August 7, 2019, when the territory's [[Supreme Court of Puerto Rico|Supreme Court]] ruled his assumption of office was unconstitutional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ramajudicial.pr/Prensa/comunicados/2019/08-07-19b.htm|title=Portal de la Rama Judicial de Puerto Rico|website=www.ramajudicial.pr|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref> He\u2019s the cousin of musician [[Draco Rosa]].\n\nHe served as the [[Secretary of Justice of Puerto Rico]] in the 1990s, as well as served as the [[Resident Commissioner of Puerto Rico]] in 2009\u20132017 in the [[United States Congress|Congress]]. Before serving in Congress, Pierluisi worked in the private and public sectors as a lobbyist. Pierluisi, a member of [[New Progressive Party of Puerto Rico|New Progressive]] and the [[United States Democratic Party|national Democratic Party]] was appointed the acting [[Secretary of State of Puerto Rico]] in July 2019, and assumed the office of governor on August 2, 2019 upon the resignation of [[Ricardo Rossell\u00f3]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Clark |first=Bill |work=NBC News |title=Puerto Rico Legislature delays vote on Pedro Pierluisi, possible successor to governor |date=August 1, 2019 |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/puerto-rico-legislature-delays-vote-pedro-pierluisi-possible-successor-governor-n1038431}}</ref> Pierluisi stated that if the Senate of Puerto Rico didn't confirm or validate his position as former Secretary of State, he would resign the governorship.<ref> {{cite news |work=Noticel |title=Pierluisi comienza a atar cabos con jefes de agencias |date=August 3, 2019 | accessdate=August 3, 2019 |url=https://www.noticel.com/ahora/pierluisi-comienza-a-atar-cabos-con-jefes-de-agencias/1103270883}}</ref>  However, he subsequently walked back that statement. On August 5, 2019, the Puerto Rico Senate filed a lawsuit against his appointment as governor.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/latino/456201-puerto-rico-senate-sues-to-oust-new-governor|title=Puerto Rico Senate sues to oust new governor|first=Ian|last=Swanson|date=August 5, 2019|website=TheHill}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/08/puerto-rico-senate-governor-illegitimate-190806071625685.html|title=Puerto Rico: Senate says new governor is illegitimate|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> Two days later, the Puerto Rico Supreme Court ruled that Pierluisi was sworn in on unconstitutional grounds and removed him from office, effective 5 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|AST]] on August 7, to be replaced by [[Wanda V\u00e1zquez Garced]], the Secretary of Justice.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |author1=D\u00c1NICA COTO |title=Puerto Rico High Court Overturns Pedro Pierluisi as Governor |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-08-07/urgent-puerto-rico-high-court-overturns-pedro-pierluisi-as-governor |agency=THE ASSOCIATED PRESS |publisher=Bloomberg News |date=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/07/us/puerto-rico-governor-supreme-court-pierluisi.html|title=Puerto Rico Supreme Court Rules New Governor Was Unlawfully Sworn In|last=Mazzei|first=Patricia|date=2019-08-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-07|last2=Robles|first2=Frances|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nPierluisi was born in 1959 in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]].  He attended [[Colegio Marista Guaynabo|Colegio Marista]] of [[Guaynabo, Puerto Rico|Guaynabo]], graduating in 1977.  In 1981, he received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[American History]] from [[Tulane University]], and later earned a [[Juris Doctor]] degree from [[George Washington University Law School]] in 1984. He was President of the [[Puerto Rico Statehood Students Association]] chapter at Tulane University.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statehoodpr.org |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080327232705/http://www.statehoodpr.org/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-03-27 |title=Free Hosting Account Suspended - x10hosting |website=Statehoodpr.org |accessdate=2016-04-28 }}</ref>  Later, he was President of the George Washington University International Law Society from 1982\u20131983.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} During his studies at George Washington University, Pierluisi [[Internship#United States|interned]] at the congressional office of then-[[Resident Commissioner of Puerto Rico]] [[Baltasar Corrada del R\u00edo]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}.\n\n== Early career ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=August 2019}}\nPierluisi first practiced law as a private attorney in [[Washington, D.C.]] from 1984 until 1990.  Notably, Mr. Pierluisi was one of the lead attorneys representing the [[government of Peru]] in its lawsuit against the Hunt brothers, [[Nelson Bunker Hunt|Nelson Bunker]], [[William Herbert Hunt|William Herbert]], and [[Lamar Hunt|Lamar]] for trying to corner the [[Silver Thursday|silver market]] in the late 1970s.  The lawsuit resulted in a $180 million damages award for the plaintiff. He then practiced law in Puerto Rico from 1990 until 1993.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nIn 1993, Governor [[Pedro Rossello]] nominated Pierluisi to serve as Puerto Rico's Secretary of Justice. His nomination was unanimously confirmed by the Puerto Rican legislature.\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n{{see also|United States House of Representatives election in Puerto Rico, 2008}}On May 18, 2007, Pierluisi announced his candidacy for [[Resident Commissioner]], Puerto Rico's sole delegate to the United States Congress in the November 2008 elections. He accompanied then current Resident Commissioner and gubernatorial candidate [[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]]  in the [[New Progressive Party primaries, 2008|March 9, 2008 NPP primary]] ticket. Fortu\u00f1o was a classmate at Colegio Marista, a fellow founding member of the [[Puerto Rico Statehood Students Association]] in 1979, and also a fellow cabinet member of Pierluisi's during Governor Rossell\u00f3's first term from 1993\u20131996.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nAccording to the candidate reports filed before the [[Federal Elections Commission]] (FEC),<ref name=\"Federal Elections Commission\">{{cite web |url= http://herndon1.sdrdc.com/cgi-bin/cancomsrs/?_08+H8PR00062 |title= Pedro Pierluisi Total Receipts|accessdate=2008-06-11 |author=FEC 2007\u20132008 Cycle |date=2008-06-11 |publisher=FEC}}</ref> Pierluisi led the other NPP candidates by a ten-to-one margin in fundraising, having raised over $450,000 in 2007, while opponent [[Charlie Rodriguez]] had only raised $47,000 and Dr. [[Miriam Ram\u00edrez de Ferrer]] had not reported any fundraising. He also leads in fundraising among the four candidates to succeed Resident Commissioner Fortu\u00f1o in the November 4, 2008 general election.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nOn March 9, 2008, Pierluisi won the primary with 61% of the vote against former Senate President Charlie Rodriguez, who polled 33%, and former Sen. Miriam Ram\u00edrez, who obtained 6% of the vote.  Pierluisi's running mate, Luis Fortu\u00f1o, also won the NPP nomination for governor with nearly 60% of primary votes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://64.185.222.182/Primarias/escrutinio/PNP/Default.htm |title=Primarias 2008 Escrutinio PNP |website=64.185.222.182 |accessdate=2016-04-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303212622/http://64.185.222.182/Primarias/escrutinio/PNP/Default.htm |archivedate=2016-03-03 }}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 2008, he won the post of [[Resident Commissioner of Puerto Rico]] with over 53% of the vote.  He was sworn in on January 6, 2009 by House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]]. He was the top vote-getter in the 2012 general elections, when he was reelected to a second four-year term and outpolled his running-mate, then Gov. Luis Fortu\u00f1o as well as current Gov. Alejandro Garc\u00eda Padilla.  He had more seniority in the House than the congressman who is 254th on the list of seniority.\n\nPierluisi is a member of the [[New Progressive Party of Puerto Rico|New Progressive Party]] in Puerto Rico which advocates statehood for the Island territory. He and former Governor [[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]], both of the New Progressive Party, beat their rivals by over one million votes - the largest margin of victory for a Resident Commissioner in Puerto Rico's history. While on [[Capitol Hill, Washington, D.C.|Capitol Hill]], Pierluisi caucused with the [[House Democratic Caucus]].<ref name=\"nationaljournal1\">Newlin, Eliza. [http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2010/person/pedro-pierluisi-pr/ Res. Com. Pedro Pierluisi (D-PR, At-Large) \u2013 The Almanac of American Politics]. Nationaljournal.com. Retrieved on 2012-11-22.</ref> He was the sole representative in Congress of the 3.7 million American citizens who reside on the Island.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nAs Resident Commissioner, Pierluisi focused most of his congressional efforts on bills related to Puerto Rico. He introduced [[Puerto Rico Democracy Act|H.R. 2499]], which sought to provide for a [[plebiscite]] to be held in Puerto Rico to determine [[Political status of Puerto Rico|the island's ultimate political status]]. The bill was passed by the House of Representatives but did not receive a vote in the [[United States Senate|Senate]], and lapsed following the [[Adjournment sine die|sine die adjournment]] of the 111th Congress. In a separate bill, [https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr870 H.R. 870], Pierluisi sought to add Puerto Rico to [[Chapter 9, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 9 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code]] so that [[List of government-owned corporations of Puerto Rico|the island's government-owned corporations]] could file for bankruptcy \u2014 a privilege they do not enjoy due to the territory's exclusion from the code. The bill was a fallback against the [[Puerto Rican government-debt crisis]], which threatens local agencies that are unable to restructure their debt.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nIn a move unrelated to H.R. 2499, a political status referendum was held in Puerto Rico on November 6, 2012. 54% of voters expressed their desire for Puerto Rico's political status to be changed. In a separate vote on the same ballot, 61% supported statehood for Puerto Rico. Consequently, on May 15, 2013, Pierluisi filed H.R. 2000, a bill to admit Puerto Rico as a state.<ref>[http://www.puertoricoreport.org/pierluisi-introduces-historic-legislation/ \u2013 Puerto Rico Report]. PuertoRicoReport.com (2013-05-15). Retrieved on 2013-05-13.</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Ethics|Committee on Ethics]]'''\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security|Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism and Homeland Security]]\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Immigration Policy and Enforcement|Subcommittee on Immigration Policy and Enforcement]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n**[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Fisheries, Wildlife, Oceans and Insular Affairs|Subcommittee on Fisheries, Wildlife, Oceans and Insular Affairs]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* Congressional Arts Caucus\n* [[Congressional Hispanic Caucus]]\n\n===Accusations of conflicts of interest===\nIn April 2016, while legislation to deal with Puerto Rico's fiscal crisis was being discussed in the House of Representatives, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published an article covering possible conflicts of interest involving Pierluisi.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/13/us/politics/puerto-ricos-prosperous-dc-power-couple.html?_r=0|title=Puerto Rico's Prosperous D.C. Power Couple|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2016-04-28}}</ref> The article covers various corporate clients from Pierluisi's wife personal firm who would benefit directly from bills proposed by Pierluisi, specifically those amending Chapter 9 of the Federal Bankruptcy Code. These firms had recently invested in Puerto Rican bonds. In addition, the newspaper established that Pierluisi's wife founded the firm shortly after Pierluisi was sworn into Congress in 2009. In the 8 years since he was elected resident commissioner, Pierluisi's average net worth had increased 27-fold.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efe.com/efe/english/world/puerto-rico-rep-in-d-c-profiting-from-wife-s-wall-street-ties/50000262-2895700|title=Puerto Rico rep in D.C. profiting from wife's Wall Street ties|website=www.efe.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://waragainstallpuertoricans.com/2016/07/07/these-are-the-puerto-ricans-who-owe-72-billion-to-the-united-statesand-they-should-pay-it/|title=THESE are the Puerto Ricans who owe $72 billion to the United States\u2026and THEY should pay it|date=July 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Participant in the \"race\" for Puerto Rico's governance Post-Rossell\u00f3's Resignation==\n\n=== Tenure as Governor of Puerto Rico ===\n{{see also|Telegramgate}}On July 30, 2019, local media in Puerto Rico reported that the embattled governor, [[Ricardo Rossell\u00f3]], nominated Pierluisi to serve as Secretary of State of Puerto Rico. He was additionally sworn into the role as a recess appointment on July 31, 2019. Governor Rossell\u00f3 then summoned Puerto Rico's Congress for them to issue their advice and consent. The House of Representatives approved his nomination 26-21.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2Mx9oei|title=Puerto Rico governor resigns as promised; successor sworn in|last=Press|first=Associated|website=POLITICO}}</ref> However, the following day, members of the Puerto Rican Senate announced that action on his nomination would not occur before August 1, 2019. Upon Rossell\u00f3's resignation on August 2, 2019, Rossell\u00f3 declared Pierluisi governor despite not having been confirmed by both the House and Senate as secretary of state, and Pierluisi affirmed Rossell\u00f3's declaration. Pierluisi's accession to the governorship was challenged in the courts as being unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/02/us/puerto-rico-governor/index.html|title=Pedro Pierluisi was sworn in as Puerto Rico's governor. His opponents are still questioning his legitimacy.|date=August 2, 2019|work=CNN|accessdate=August 2, 2019}}</ref> On August 5, 2019, the Puerto Rico Senate filed a lawsuit against his appointment as Governor contending that unless he obtains the Senate's assent, his governorship is unconstitutional.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/> Two days later, the Puerto Rico Supreme Court ruled that Pierluisi was sworn in on unconstitutional grounds and, that he be removed from office effective 5 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|AST]] on August 7.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nPierluisi's father, Jorge Pierluisi, served as Secretary of [[Puerto Rico Department of Housing|Puerto Rico's Housing Department]] under Gov. [[Carlos Romero Barcel\u00f3]] from 1977 to 1985. His brother, [[Jos\u00e9 Jaime Pierluisi]], an economic adviser to then governor [[Pedro Rossello]], was shot and killed during a carjacking in 1994.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/06/11/obituaries/jose-jaime-pierluisi-28-an-aide-to-puerto-rico-governor-dies.html|title=Jose Jaime Pierluisi, 28, an Aide To Puerto Rico Governor, Dies|date=June 11, 1994|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Politics|Puerto Rico|United States}}\n* [[List of Hispanic Americans in the United States Congress]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{C-SPAN|pedropierluisi}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090114072326/http://pierluisi.house.gov/ Congressman Pedro Pierluisi] ''official U.S. House website''\n* [http://www.pierluisi2008.com/ Pedro Pierluisi for Congress] (Spanish) ''official campaign website''\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=P000596 | votesmart=110894 | fec=H8PR00062 | congress= }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/412306 Congressional profile] at [[GovTrack]]\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00029168&newmem=Y Financial information (federal office)] at [[Center for Responsive Politics|OpenSecrets.org]]\n* [http://www.legistorm.com/member/988/Rep_Pedro_Pierluisi.html Staff salaries, trips and personal finance] at LegiStorm.com\n* -->\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[H\u00e9ctor Rivera Cruz]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of Justice of Puerto Rico]]|years=1993\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jos\u00e9 Fuentes Agostini]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Resident Commissioner of Puerto Rico]]|years=2009\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jenniffer Gonz\u00e1lez]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Presidents of the New Progressive Party of Puerto Rico|Chair of the Puerto Rico New Progressive Party]]|years=2013\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ricardo Rossell\u00f3]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Luis G. Rivera Mar\u00edn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State of Puerto Rico]]<br>Acting|years=2019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Elmer Rom\u00e1n]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ricardo Rossell\u00f3]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of Puerto Rico]]<br>''[[De facto]]''|years=2019 }}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Wanda V\u00e1zquez Garced]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Puerto Rico Governors}}\n{{PRResidentComm}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pierluisi Urrutia, Pedro Rafael}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (Puerto Rico) politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:George Washington University Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Progressive Party (Puerto Rico) politicians]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican lawyers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Statehood movement in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rico Statehood Students Association alumni]]\n[[Category:Resident Commissioners of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Justice of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Puerto Rican politician}}\n{{spanish name|Pierluisi|Urrutia}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Pedro R. Pierluisi\n| image = Pedro-Pierluisi-cropped.jpg\n<!-- While his swearing in was deemed unconstitutional and he was duly removed from office on August 7, 2019, it is undeniable that Pierluisi did indeed serve and occupy the post of Governor and it should remain in the infobox. The details of his short term should be described in the prose as supported by reliable sourcing. -->\n| office = [[Governor of Puerto Rico]]<br>''{{small|[[De facto]]}}''\n| term_start = August 2, 2019\n| term_end = August 7, 2019{{efn|Pierluisi was removed on August 7, 2019, via ''[[quo warranto]]''. Hence, his tenure is now considered only ''[[de facto]]''.}}\n| predecessor = [[Ricardo Rossell\u00f3]]\n| successor = [[Wanda V\u00e1zquez Garced]]\n<!-- While his swearing in was deemed unconstitutional and he was duly removed from office on August 7, 2019, it is undeniable that Pierluisi did indeed serve and occupy the post of Governor and it should remain in the infobox. The details of his short term should be described in the prose as supported by reliable sourcing. -->\n| office1 = Acting [[Secretary of State of Puerto Rico]]\n| governor1 = [[Ricardo Rossell\u00f3]]\n| term_start1 = July 31, 2019\n| term_end1 = August 2, 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Luis G. Rivera Mar\u00edn|Luis Rivera Mar\u00edn]]\n| successor1 = [[Elmer Rom\u00e1n]]\n| office2 = [[Resident Commissioner of Puerto Rico]]\n| term_start2 = January 3, 2009\n| term_end2 = January 3, 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]]\n| successor2 = [[Jenniffer Gonz\u00e1lez]]\n| office3 = [[Secretary of Justice of Puerto Rico]]\n| governor3 = [[Pedro Rossell\u00f3]]\n| term_start3 = January 2, 1993\n| term_end3 = January 2, 1997\n| predecessor3 = H\u00e9ctor Rivera Cruz\n| successor3 = Jos\u00e9 Fuentes Agostini\n| birth_name = Pedro Rafael Pierluisi Urrutia\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|4|26}}\n| birth_place = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Puerto Rico]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[New Progressive Party of Puerto Rico|New Progressive]]\n| otherparty = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| children = 4\n| education = [[Tulane University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])<br />[[George Washington University]] ([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]])\n| relations = [[Jos\u00e9 Jaime Pierluisi]] (brother)<br />\n}}\n'''Pedro Pierluisi Urrutia'''{{efn|Primera Hora (2009) \"El nuevo comisionado residente en Washington, Pedro Rafael Pierluisi Urrutia...\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.primerahora.com/noticias/gobierno-politica/nota/buscaauxiliofederal-261641/ |title=Busca auxilio federal |date={{date|2009-01-07|mdy}} |newspaper=[[Primera Hora (Puerto Rico)|Primera Hora]] |language=Spanish |accessdate={{date|2013-09-02|mdy}} }}</ref>}} (born April 26, 1959) is a Puerto Rican [[lawyer|attorney]], lobbyist,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.senado.pr.gov:443/Pages/Registro-de-Cabilderos.aspx|title=Senado Registro de Cabilderos|website=www.senado.pr.gov|language=es|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref> and politician who served as ''[[de facto]]'' [[governor of Puerto Rico]] from August 2 to August 7, 2019, when the territory's [[Supreme Court of Puerto Rico|Supreme Court]] ruled his assumption of office was unconstitutional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ramajudicial.pr/Prensa/comunicados/2019/08-07-19b.htm|title=Portal de la Rama Judicial de Puerto Rico|website=www.ramajudicial.pr|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref>\n\nHe served as the [[Secretary of Justice of Puerto Rico]] in the 1990s, as well as served as the [[Resident Commissioner of Puerto Rico]] in 2009\u20132017 in the [[United States Congress|Congress]]. Before serving in Congress, Pierluisi worked in the private and public sectors as a lobbyist. Pierluisi, a member of [[New Progressive Party of Puerto Rico|New Progressive]] and the [[United States Democratic Party|national Democratic Party]] was appointed the acting [[Secretary of State of Puerto Rico]] in July 2019, and assumed the office of governor on August 2, 2019 upon the resignation of [[Ricardo Rossell\u00f3]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Clark |first=Bill |work=NBC News |title=Puerto Rico Legislature delays vote on Pedro Pierluisi, possible successor to governor |date=August 1, 2019 |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/puerto-rico-legislature-delays-vote-pedro-pierluisi-possible-successor-governor-n1038431}}</ref> Pierluisi stated that if the Senate of Puerto Rico didn't confirm or validate his position as former Secretary of State, he would resign the governorship.<ref> {{cite news |work=Noticel |title=Pierluisi comienza a atar cabos con jefes de agencias |date=August 3, 2019 | accessdate=August 3, 2019 |url=https://www.noticel.com/ahora/pierluisi-comienza-a-atar-cabos-con-jefes-de-agencias/1103270883}}</ref>  However, he subsequently walked back that statement. On August 5, 2019, the Puerto Rico Senate filed a lawsuit against his appointment as governor.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/latino/456201-puerto-rico-senate-sues-to-oust-new-governor|title=Puerto Rico Senate sues to oust new governor|first=Ian|last=Swanson|date=August 5, 2019|website=TheHill}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/08/puerto-rico-senate-governor-illegitimate-190806071625685.html|title=Puerto Rico: Senate says new governor is illegitimate|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> Two days later, the Puerto Rico Supreme Court ruled that Pierluisi was sworn in on unconstitutional grounds and removed him from office, effective 5 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|AST]] on August 7, to be replaced by [[Wanda V\u00e1zquez Garced]], the Secretary of Justice.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |author1=D\u00c1NICA COTO |title=Puerto Rico High Court Overturns Pedro Pierluisi as Governor |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-08-07/urgent-puerto-rico-high-court-overturns-pedro-pierluisi-as-governor |agency=THE ASSOCIATED PRESS |publisher=Bloomberg News |date=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/07/us/puerto-rico-governor-supreme-court-pierluisi.html|title=Puerto Rico Supreme Court Rules New Governor Was Unlawfully Sworn In|last=Mazzei|first=Patricia|date=2019-08-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-07|last2=Robles|first2=Frances|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nPierluisi was born in 1959 in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]].  He attended [[Colegio Marista Guaynabo|Colegio Marista]] of [[Guaynabo, Puerto Rico|Guaynabo]], graduating in 1977.  In 1981, he received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[American History]] from [[Tulane University]], and later earned a [[Juris Doctor]] degree from [[George Washington University Law School]] in 1984. He was President of the [[Puerto Rico Statehood Students Association]] chapter at Tulane University.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statehoodpr.org |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080327232705/http://www.statehoodpr.org/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-03-27 |title=Free Hosting Account Suspended - x10hosting |website=Statehoodpr.org |accessdate=2016-04-28 }}</ref>  Later, he was President of the George Washington University International Law Society from 1982\u20131983.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} During his studies at George Washington University, Pierluisi [[Internship#United States|interned]] at the congressional office of then-[[Resident Commissioner of Puerto Rico]] [[Baltasar Corrada del R\u00edo]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}.\n\n== Early career ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=August 2019}}\nPierluisi first practiced law as a private attorney in [[Washington, D.C.]] from 1984 until 1990.  Notably, Mr. Pierluisi was one of the lead attorneys representing the [[government of Peru]] in its lawsuit against the Hunt brothers, [[Nelson Bunker Hunt|Nelson Bunker]], [[William Herbert Hunt|William Herbert]], and [[Lamar Hunt|Lamar]] for trying to corner the [[Silver Thursday|silver market]] in the late 1970s.  The lawsuit resulted in a $180 million damages award for the plaintiff. He then practiced law in Puerto Rico from 1990 until 1993.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nIn 1993, Governor [[Pedro Rossello]] nominated Pierluisi to serve as Puerto Rico's Secretary of Justice. His nomination was unanimously confirmed by the Puerto Rican legislature.\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n{{see also|United States House of Representatives election in Puerto Rico, 2008}}On May 18, 2007, Pierluisi announced his candidacy for [[Resident Commissioner]], Puerto Rico's sole delegate to the United States Congress in the November 2008 elections. He accompanied then current Resident Commissioner and gubernatorial candidate [[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]]  in the [[New Progressive Party primaries, 2008|March 9, 2008 NPP primary]] ticket. Fortu\u00f1o was a classmate at Colegio Marista, a fellow founding member of the [[Puerto Rico Statehood Students Association]] in 1979, and also a fellow cabinet member of Pierluisi's during Governor Rossell\u00f3's first term from 1993\u20131996.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nAccording to the candidate reports filed before the [[Federal Elections Commission]] (FEC),<ref name=\"Federal Elections Commission\">{{cite web |url= http://herndon1.sdrdc.com/cgi-bin/cancomsrs/?_08+H8PR00062 |title= Pedro Pierluisi Total Receipts|accessdate=2008-06-11 |author=FEC 2007\u20132008 Cycle |date=2008-06-11 |publisher=FEC}}</ref> Pierluisi led the other NPP candidates by a ten-to-one margin in fundraising, having raised over $450,000 in 2007, while opponent [[Charlie Rodriguez]] had only raised $47,000 and Dr. [[Miriam Ram\u00edrez de Ferrer]] had not reported any fundraising. He also leads in fundraising among the four candidates to succeed Resident Commissioner Fortu\u00f1o in the November 4, 2008 general election.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nOn March 9, 2008, Pierluisi won the primary with 61% of the vote against former Senate President Charlie Rodriguez, who polled 33%, and former Sen. Miriam Ram\u00edrez, who obtained 6% of the vote.  Pierluisi's running mate, Luis Fortu\u00f1o, also won the NPP nomination for governor with nearly 60% of primary votes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://64.185.222.182/Primarias/escrutinio/PNP/Default.htm |title=Primarias 2008 Escrutinio PNP |website=64.185.222.182 |accessdate=2016-04-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303212622/http://64.185.222.182/Primarias/escrutinio/PNP/Default.htm |archivedate=2016-03-03 }}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 2008, he won the post of [[Resident Commissioner of Puerto Rico]] with over 53% of the vote.  He was sworn in on January 6, 2009 by House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]]. He was the top vote-getter in the 2012 general elections, when he was reelected to a second four-year term and outpolled his running-mate, then Gov. Luis Fortu\u00f1o as well as current Gov. Alejandro Garc\u00eda Padilla.  He had more seniority in the House than the congressman who is 254th on the list of seniority.\n\nPierluisi is a member of the [[New Progressive Party of Puerto Rico|New Progressive Party]] in Puerto Rico which advocates statehood for the Island territory. He and former Governor [[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]], both of the New Progressive Party, beat their rivals by over one million votes - the largest margin of victory for a Resident Commissioner in Puerto Rico's history. While on [[Capitol Hill, Washington, D.C.|Capitol Hill]], Pierluisi caucused with the [[House Democratic Caucus]].<ref name=\"nationaljournal1\">Newlin, Eliza. [http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2010/person/pedro-pierluisi-pr/ Res. Com. Pedro Pierluisi (D-PR, At-Large) \u2013 The Almanac of American Politics]. Nationaljournal.com. Retrieved on 2012-11-22.</ref> He was the sole representative in Congress of the 3.7 million American citizens who reside on the Island.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nAs Resident Commissioner, Pierluisi focused most of his congressional efforts on bills related to Puerto Rico. He introduced [[Puerto Rico Democracy Act|H.R. 2499]], which sought to provide for a [[plebiscite]] to be held in Puerto Rico to determine [[Political status of Puerto Rico|the island's ultimate political status]]. The bill was passed by the House of Representatives but did not receive a vote in the [[United States Senate|Senate]], and lapsed following the [[Adjournment sine die|sine die adjournment]] of the 111th Congress. In a separate bill, [https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr870 H.R. 870], Pierluisi sought to add Puerto Rico to [[Chapter 9, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 9 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code]] so that [[List of government-owned corporations of Puerto Rico|the island's government-owned corporations]] could file for bankruptcy \u2014 a privilege they do not enjoy due to the territory's exclusion from the code. The bill was a fallback against the [[Puerto Rican government-debt crisis]], which threatens local agencies that are unable to restructure their debt.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nIn a move unrelated to H.R. 2499, a political status referendum was held in Puerto Rico on November 6, 2012. 54% of voters expressed their desire for Puerto Rico's political status to be changed. In a separate vote on the same ballot, 61% supported statehood for Puerto Rico. Consequently, on May 15, 2013, Pierluisi filed H.R. 2000, a bill to admit Puerto Rico as a state.<ref>[http://www.puertoricoreport.org/pierluisi-introduces-historic-legislation/ \u2013 Puerto Rico Report]. PuertoRicoReport.com (2013-05-15). Retrieved on 2013-05-13.</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Ethics|Committee on Ethics]]'''\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security|Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism and Homeland Security]]\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Immigration Policy and Enforcement|Subcommittee on Immigration Policy and Enforcement]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n**[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Fisheries, Wildlife, Oceans and Insular Affairs|Subcommittee on Fisheries, Wildlife, Oceans and Insular Affairs]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* Congressional Arts Caucus\n* [[Congressional Hispanic Caucus]]\n\n===Accusations of conflicts of interest===\nIn April 2016, while legislation to deal with Puerto Rico's fiscal crisis was being discussed in the House of Representatives, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published an article covering possible conflicts of interest involving Pierluisi.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/13/us/politics/puerto-ricos-prosperous-dc-power-couple.html?_r=0|title=Puerto Rico's Prosperous D.C. Power Couple|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2016-04-28}}</ref> The article covers various corporate clients from Pierluisi's wife personal firm who would benefit directly from bills proposed by Pierluisi, specifically those amending Chapter 9 of the Federal Bankruptcy Code. These firms had recently invested in Puerto Rican bonds. In addition, the newspaper established that Pierluisi's wife founded the firm shortly after Pierluisi was sworn into Congress in 2009. In the 8 years since he was elected resident commissioner, Pierluisi's average net worth had increased 27-fold.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efe.com/efe/english/world/puerto-rico-rep-in-d-c-profiting-from-wife-s-wall-street-ties/50000262-2895700|title=Puerto Rico rep in D.C. profiting from wife's Wall Street ties|website=www.efe.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://waragainstallpuertoricans.com/2016/07/07/these-are-the-puerto-ricans-who-owe-72-billion-to-the-united-statesand-they-should-pay-it/|title=THESE are the Puerto Ricans who owe $72 billion to the United States\u2026and THEY should pay it|date=July 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Participant in the \"race\" for Puerto Rico's governance Post-Rossell\u00f3's Resignation==\n\n=== Tenure as Governor of Puerto Rico ===\n{{see also|Telegramgate}}On July 30, 2019, local media in Puerto Rico reported that the embattled governor, [[Ricardo Rossell\u00f3]], nominated Pierluisi to serve as Secretary of State of Puerto Rico. He was additionally sworn into the role as a recess appointment on July 31, 2019. Governor Rossell\u00f3 then summoned Puerto Rico's Congress for them to issue their advice and consent. The House of Representatives approved his nomination 26-21.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2Mx9oei|title=Puerto Rico governor resigns as promised; successor sworn in|last=Press|first=Associated|website=POLITICO}}</ref> However, the following day, members of the Puerto Rican Senate announced that action on his nomination would not occur before August 1, 2019. Upon Rossell\u00f3's resignation on August 2, 2019, Rossell\u00f3 declared Pierluisi governor despite not having been confirmed by both the House and Senate as secretary of state, and Pierluisi affirmed Rossell\u00f3's declaration. Pierluisi's accession to the governorship was challenged in the courts as being unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/02/us/puerto-rico-governor/index.html|title=Pedro Pierluisi was sworn in as Puerto Rico's governor. His opponents are still questioning his legitimacy.|date=August 2, 2019|work=CNN|accessdate=August 2, 2019}}</ref> On August 5, 2019, the Puerto Rico Senate filed a lawsuit against his appointment as Governor contending that unless he obtains the Senate's assent, his governorship is unconstitutional.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/> Two days later, the Puerto Rico Supreme Court ruled that Pierluisi was sworn in on unconstitutional grounds and, that he be removed from office effective 5 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|AST]] on August 7.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nPierluisi's father, Jorge Pierluisi, served as Secretary of [[Puerto Rico Department of Housing|Puerto Rico's Housing Department]] under Gov. [[Carlos Romero Barcel\u00f3]] from 1977 to 1985. His brother, [[Jos\u00e9 Jaime Pierluisi]], an economic adviser to then governor [[Pedro Rossello]], was shot and killed during a carjacking in 1994.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/06/11/obituaries/jose-jaime-pierluisi-28-an-aide-to-puerto-rico-governor-dies.html|title=Jose Jaime Pierluisi, 28, an Aide To Puerto Rico Governor, Dies|date=June 11, 1994|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Politics|Puerto Rico|United States}}\n* [[List of Hispanic Americans in the United States Congress]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{C-SPAN|pedropierluisi}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090114072326/http://pierluisi.house.gov/ Congressman Pedro Pierluisi] ''official U.S. House website''\n* [http://www.pierluisi2008.com/ Pedro Pierluisi for Congress] (Spanish) ''official campaign website''\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=P000596 | votesmart=110894 | fec=H8PR00062 | congress= }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/412306 Congressional profile] at [[GovTrack]]\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00029168&newmem=Y Financial information (federal office)] at [[Center for Responsive Politics|OpenSecrets.org]]\n* [http://www.legistorm.com/member/988/Rep_Pedro_Pierluisi.html Staff salaries, trips and personal finance] at LegiStorm.com\n* -->\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[H\u00e9ctor Rivera Cruz]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of Justice of Puerto Rico]]|years=1993\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jos\u00e9 Fuentes Agostini]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Resident Commissioner of Puerto Rico]]|years=2009\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jenniffer Gonz\u00e1lez]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Presidents of the New Progressive Party of Puerto Rico|Chair of the Puerto Rico New Progressive Party]]|years=2013\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ricardo Rossell\u00f3]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Luis G. Rivera Mar\u00edn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State of Puerto Rico]]<br>Acting|years=2019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Elmer Rom\u00e1n]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ricardo Rossell\u00f3]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of Puerto Rico]]<br>''[[De facto]]''|years=2019 }}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Wanda V\u00e1zquez Garced]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Puerto Rico Governors}}\n{{PRResidentComm}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pierluisi Urrutia, Pedro Rafael}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (Puerto Rico) politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:George Washington University Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Progressive Party (Puerto Rico) politicians]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican lawyers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Statehood movement in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rico Statehood Students Association alumni]]\n[[Category:Resident Commissioners of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Justice of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "24.48.215.37", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pedro_Pierluisi"}
